1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ While working on the course, I found myself in an unusual situation. There is practically no modern theory! So I feel like a pioneer in a way. In this part I'll try to highlight the most frequent directions of the King's Gambit. }
2... d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit, which is normally played to deviate from all the sharp forced lines. }
3. exd5 e4
{ This is the old main line. The idea is to restrict White's knight from developing to f3. }
4. d3
{ Already gives White a solid advantage. Themain chapter goes much further down the rabbit hole. }
