1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ While working on the course, I found myself in an unusual situation. There is practically no modern theory! So I feel like a pioneer in a way. In this part I'll try to highlight the most frequent directions of the King's Gambit. }
2... exf4
{ The main continuation. White needs to be on the lookout and sometimes choose the lesser of evils. }
3. Nf3 d6
{ The most flexible move. Black doesn't give up on the g5 idea while continues normal development. }
4. Bc4 h6
{ Another flexible useful move.  4...g5  is a little bit premature because of  5.h4  with pressure on both the g- and f-pawns. }
5. h4
{ We will have to fight against the g7-g5 plan, otherwise we will have to face the consequences. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Nc6 { Both sides are trying to develop harmoniously. } 7. d4
Nh5 8. Nd5
{ White is ready to win the pawn back and finish development at the same time. }
*

