1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ While working on the course, I found myself in an unusual situation. There is practically no modern theory! So I feel like a pioneer in a way. In this part I'll try to highlight the most frequent directions of the King's Gambit. }
2... exf4
{ The main continuation. White needs to be on the lookout and sometimes choose the lesser of evils. }
3. Nf3 g5
{ This move is being played more often than others. Black protects on f4 and prepares further advancing of the pawn. }
4. h4
{ It is important to undermine the pawn structure and prevent the queen from reaching h4. }
4... g4 5. Ne5 Nf6 6. Nxg4
{ We have to be ready to enter the complications.  6.Bc4  d5  is simply not good enough. }
6... Nxe4 7. d3 Ng3 8. Bxf4 { An important forced line starts with } 8... Nxh1
9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. Nf6+ Kd8 11. Bxc7+ Kxc7 12. Nd5+
{ And we reach an unclear position where the material balance is breached, although it is always nice to have a queen! This line is further annotated in the3...g5 chapter. }
*

