[Black "2...f5? #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... f5
{ Gioachino Greco tried this in 1620, but even that won't make this move better. }
3. exf5 { Black can't develop properly because of Qh5+ threat. } 3... Qh4+ 4.
g3 Qe7 5. Bg2
{ Our plan is simple: develop pieces and win.  5.Qh5+  is also fine, but for the educational purposes I'd like to leave the full game here.  5...Kd8  6.fxe5  Qxe5+  7.Be2  Nf6  8.Qf3  d5  9.g4  h5  10.h3  hxg4  11.hxg4  Rxh1  12.Qxh1  Qg3+  13.Kd1  Nxg4  14.Qxd5+  Bd7  15.Nf3  Nf2+  16.Ke1  Nd3+  17.Kd1  Qe1+  18.Nxe1  Nf2#  0-1 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ NN-Greco,G Europe 1620. }
5... exf4+ 6. Ne2 fxg3 7. O-O
{ This is completely unplayable for Black. Not only hasn't he developed a single piece yet, his queen even impedes his development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
