[White "Chapter 1: 2...Nf6, 2...c6, and Other Rare Moves"]
[Black "2...f5? #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... f5
{ Gioachino Greco tried this in 1620, but even that won't make this move better. }
3. exf5 { Black can't develop properly because of Qh5+ threat. } 3... Qe7
{ Makes a bit more sense than  3...Qh4+  . Again, we simply play for development. }
4. Nf3 e4 { Probably the best attempt for Black. } 5. Ng5 Nf6 6. Be2
{ One of our ideas is to use the h5-e8 diagonal to give this very nasty check. }
6... d5 7. Bh5+ Kd7 8. O-O c6 9. d3
{ Open the center, close the game. Black's king is exposed and he is a pawn down. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: 2...Nf6, 2...c6, and Other Rare Moves"]
[Black "2...Qh4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... Qh4+ { This simply can't be a good move. } 3. g3 Qe7 4. Nc3 exf4 5. d4
{ One of the main concepts of any gambit - don't care too much about material and develop the pieces. }
5... fxg3 6. hxg3 d5 7. Bf4 Be6 8. Rh2 { A useful rook lift. } 8... dxe4 9. d5
Bd7 10. Qd2
{ We finish our development and simply crush our opponent in the center. O-O-O, d6 and Nxe4 are coming. You may also consider simply taking Bxc7. }
*

