1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... c6
{ This is a possible move, but looks more like another attempt to provoke White for  3.fxe5??  Qh4+  . }
3. Nf3
{ Another possible concept is  3.d3!?  exf4  4.Bxf4  d5  5.Nd2  1-0 Gufeld, E. - Saidy, A. Honolulu 1996. }
3... d5 { This breaktrough is now late. } 4. Nxe5 dxe4 5. Bc4 Nh6 6. Nc3 f6 7.
d3
{ Our knight is a symbolic price for such activity.  7.d4  Bf5  8.O-O  Nd7  9.Kh1∞  is very promising too. }
7... b5 8. Bb3 fxe5 9. Qh5+ Kd7 10. fxe5
{ Black's king is too exposed, White dominates the game. } 10... Kc7 11. e6
exd3 12. Qe5+ Qd6 13. Qe4
{ White is perfectly centralized. Perhaps, Black can hold, but it's hard to find someone who'll play like this voluntarily. }
