1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... c6
{ This is a possible move, but looks more like another attempt to provoke White for  3.fxe5??  Qh4+  . }
3. Nf3
{ Another possible concept is  3.d3!?  exf4  4.Bxf4  d5  5.Nd2  1-0 Gufeld, E. - Saidy, A. Honolulu 1996. }
3... exf4 4. d4 d5
{ This is quite similar to the Falkbeer Countergambit, but here Black has less options: Black can't support the f4-pawn with ...g5. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. exd5 { This calmer alternative seems to be OK for White. } 6...
cxd5 7. Bxf4 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Qe2+
{ In general, our idea is to exchange queens because of Black's isolated queen;s pawn @@StartBracket@@d5@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Be6 10. Qe5 { We don't have anything against endgames. } 10... Qb6 11.
O-O-O Nc6 12. Qf4 O-O 13. a3 Rac8 14. Bd3
{ It's really hard for Black to find any counterplay. Our plan is very simple though: just Rde1 and Rhf1, Ng5, g2-g4 and something like this should certainly work out well. }
