1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... c6
{ This is a possible move, but looks more like another attempt to provoke White for  3.fxe5??  Qh4+  . }
3. Nf3
{ Another possible concept is  3.d3!?  exf4  4.Bxf4  d5  5.Nd2  1-0 Gufeld, E. - Saidy, A. Honolulu 1996. }
3... exf4 4. d4 d5
{ This is quite similar to the Falkbeer Countergambit, but here Black has less options: Black can't support the f4-pawn with ...g5. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. exd5 Bd6 7. Qe2+ { It's vital to prevent Black from castling. }
7... Kf8 8. Ne5 g5 { This was played by Anand once, but it is nearly losing: }
9. h4 Nxd5 10. Bd2
{ Or  10.Nxd5  cxd5  11.Qh5  Qe7  12.Qh6+  Ke8  13.Qg7±  as in 1/2 Nunn, J. - Anand, V. Monte Carlo 1995. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O
{ This position is nowhere near playable for Black: we simply open files on the kingside with g3 and go for the direct attack. The king is really poor on f8 and Black has no counterplay. }
