[White "Chapter 1: 2...Nf6, 2...c6, and Other Rare Moves"]
[Black "2...c6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... c6
{ This is a possible move, but looks more like another attempt to provoke White for  3.fxe5??  Qh4+  . }
3. Nf3
{ Another possible concept is  3.d3!?  exf4  4.Bxf4  d5  5.Nd2  1-0 Gufeld, E. - Saidy, A. Honolulu 1996. }
3... exf4 4. d4 d5
{ This is quite similar to the Falkbeer Countergambit, but here Black has less options: Black can't support the f4-pawn with ...g5. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. exd5 Bd6 7. Qe2+ { It's vital to prevent Black from castling. }
7... Kf8 8. Ne5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qh4+ 10. Qf2
{ We don't have to do anything special, the endgame is more than fine for us! }
10... Qxf2+ 11. Kxf2 cxd5 12. Bxf4 Nc6 13. Rd1
{ One idea is Ng6+ to obtain the bishop pair. Generally, the d5-pawn remains weak and we will get the two bishops advantage. g3 followed by Bg2 is a pleasant maneuver for White too. We won't deliver a checkmate anytime soon, but a good endgame is a very decent outcome of the opening. }
*

