{ This is a possible move, but looks more like another attempt to provoke White for  3.fxe5??  Qh4+  . }
3. Nf3
{ Another possible concept is  3.d3!?  exf4  4.Bxf4  d5  5.Nd2  1-0 Gufeld, E. - Saidy, A. Honolulu 1996. }
3... exf4 4. d4 d5
{ This is quite similar to the Falkbeer Countergambit, but here Black has less options: Black can't support the f4-pawn with ...g5. }
5. Nc3 Nf6 6. exd5 Bd6 7. Qe2+ { It's vital to prevent Black from castling. }
7... Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ This endgame is equal, but it's White who is trying to pose problems. } 9.
Bc4
{ Ideally, we'd like to have two connected passed pawns on the queenside, but Black can prevent this with accurate play. }
9... b5 10. Bb3 b4 11. Ne2 Nxd5
{ White has several options now, but in general, the analysis suggests that Black can hold this position with precise play. }
12. Bxd5 cxd5 13. Bxf4 Nc6 14. a3 Ba6
{ This is good enough for Black to make a draw, but he still needs to be precise. }
15. axb4 Nxb4 16. Bxd6+ Kxd6 17. Kd2 Bxe2 18. Kxe2 Nxc2 19. Ra6+ Ke7 20. Rc1
Rhc8 21. Kd2 Nb4 22. Rxa7+ Rxa7 23. Rxc8
{ The game should end in a draw, but Black had plenty of moments where he could have gone wrong. }
*

