2... Nf6 { A solid move, after which White can fight for a small advantage. }
3. fxe5 Nxe4 4. Nf3 d5 { This gives White too many tempi. } 5. d3 Nc5 6. d4 Ne6
7. Nc3
{ White has space and a development advantage.  7.c4  is also possible. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: 2...Nf6, 2...c6, and Other Rare Moves"]
[Black "2...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... Nf6 { A solid move, after which White can fight for a small advantage. }
3. fxe5 Nxe4 4. Nf3 Ng5 { This leads to another pleasant endgame for White. }
5. d4 Nxf3+ 6. Qxf3 Qh4+ 7. Qf2
{ The King's Gambit is an interesting opening, we sacrifice some pawns and try to play for an attack. But when the opportunity presents itself, we gladly agree to playing a slightly better endgame. }
7... Qxf2+ 8. Kxf2 Nc6 9. c3 d6 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Nd2 Be6 12. Be2
{ This is a very typical and pleasant structure for White. Nc4 and Ne4 are both possible, depending on Black's actions. a4-a5 is one of the ideas too. Try to torture your opponent for as long as possible in these positions! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: 2...Nf6, 2...c6, and Other Rare Moves"]
[Black "2...Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ In this chapter I'll try to cover some rare continuations. You are not going to face these moves too often, but, as they say, forewarned is forearmed! }
2... Nf6 { A solid move, after which White can fight for a small advantage. }
3. fxe5 Nxe4 4. Nf3 Be7 5. d3
{ 5.d4  is also possible:  5...d5  6.exd6  cxd6   6...Nxd6  7.Bd3  is also decent.  7.Bd3  d5  8.O-O  Nc6  9.c4  Nb4  10.Be2  looks like a well-known Petroff line without the c7 and f2 pawns. }
5... Ng5 6. d4 O-O 7. Bd3
{ Putting the bishop onto the optimal square and looking closely at the opponent's king. }
7... Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3 d6 9. Nc3 { Our next moves are easy and natural. } 9... Nc6
10. Bf4 { Preparing O-O-O, the d4-pawn is poisoned. } 10... Nxd4
{ The pawn is poisoned. } 11. Qe4 Nf5 12. g4 Bh4+ 13. Bg3
{ Black should be happy not to resign immideately. } 13... Re8 14. O-O-O Bxg3
15. hxg3 Qg5+ 16. Qf4 { Again, White reaches a favorable endgame. } 16... Qxf4+
17. gxf4 Ne3
{ Black needs to try this because Nb5 and Nd5 were unpleasant threats. } 18.
Rde1 Ng2 19. Bxh7+ Kf8 20. Ref1
{ Black still needs to complete his development and his knight is poorly placed on g2. Our bishop can retreat to e4 with the gain of tempo and Nb5/Nd5 are still difficult to meet. Black may not be lost yet, but we're getting there. }
*

