1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5
{ The Old Classical line. Black first develops the bishop to a better position, and only then plays d7-d6. }
3. Nf3
{ We are never in a hurry to capture the pawn on e5!  3.fxe5??  Qh4+-+  . }
3... d5 { This is one more iteration of the Falkbeer Countergambit idea. } 4.
Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ An important move! White can't lose the battle for the e4-square. } 5... d4
6. fxe5 dxc3 7. exf6 cxd2+
{ Black must speed up our development in order not to lose a pawn. } 8. Bxd2
Qxf6 9. O-O-O
{ With excellent development and comfortable play. Most importantly, the bishop will come to c3, attacking the queen and the g7-pawn. White will win lots of tempi on the queen with moves like h2-h4-h5. }
