1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5
{ The Old Classical line. Black first develops the bishop to a better position, and only then plays d7-d6. }
3. Nf3
{ We are never in a hurry to capture the pawn on e5!  3.fxe5??  Qh4+-+  . }
3... d5 { This is one more iteration of the Falkbeer Countergambit idea. } 4.
Nc3 Nf6 5. Qe2
{ An important move! White can't lose the battle for the e4-square. } 5... dxe4
{ 5...Nxe4  6.Nxe4  dxe4  7.Qxe4  transposes. } 6. Nxe4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4 Nc6 8.
fxe5
{ Now we win the pawn and it's not obvious if Black can find any decent compensation. The most important thing is to hold the center. }
8... Nd4 { Forced, Black couldn't allow c3+d4. } 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Bd3
{ The check on f2 is really not a problem.  10.Qxd4  Bxd4  is just a draw. }
10... Bd7 11. Rf1 Bc6 12. Qe2
{ White needs to be precise, it's not so easy to complete the development. }
12... O-O-O 13. Bf5+ Kb8 14. c3 Qd5 15. d4 Rhe8 16. Rf4
{ With the idea of Be4! White's pawn chain is just perfect. Black's initiative will diminish with every exchange. }
