1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5
{ The Old Classical line. Black first develops the bishop to a better position, and only then plays d7-d6. }
3. Nf3
{ We are never in a hurry to capture the pawn on e5!  3.fxe5??  Qh4+-+  . }
3... d5 { This is one more iteration of the Falkbeer Countergambit idea. } 4.
Nc3 d4 5. Na4 { 5.Ne2?!  may be interesting as well. } 5... Be7 6. Nxe5 Nf6
{ Now the e4-pawn is weak and the knight on a4 is poorly placed. } 7. b3
{ White doesn't protect the e4-pawn and plays for development instead. } 7...
Nxe4 8. Qf3 Nf6 9. Bb2 O-O 10. O-O-O
{ The bishop can be developed to d3 or c4 and White has natural play: just throw the g- and h-pawns forward! Sometimes, we might even abandon the a4-knight altogether. }
