[White "Chapter 2: 2...Bc5"]
[Black "3...d5 4.Nc3 d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5
{ The Old Classical line. Black first develops the bishop to a better position, and only then plays d7-d6. }
3. Nf3
{ We are never in a hurry to capture the pawn on e5!  3.fxe5??  Qh4+-+  . }
3... d5 { This is one more iteration of the Falkbeer Countergambit idea. } 4.
Nc3 d4 5. Na4 { 5.Ne2?!  may be interesting as well. } 5... Bd6
{ This is more principled than  5...Be7  . } 6. fxe5 Bxe5 7. Bc4
{ 7.Nxe5  starts a long forced line which likely ends in a draw.  7...Qh4+  8.g3  Qxe4+  9.Qe2  Qxh1  10.b3  Nf6  11.Ng6+  Be6  12.Nxh8  Nbd7  13.Bb2  O-O-O  14.O-O-O  Bg4  15.Bh3!  Qxd1+  16.Qxd1  Bxd1  17.Nxf7  Rf8  18.Ne5  Be2  19.Nc5  Bb5  20.a4  Re8  21.Bxd4  b6  22.axb5  bxc5  23.Bc3  Kd8  24.Nc6+  Kc8=  . }
7... Nc6 { 7...Bg4  will never work because of the typical trick  8.Bxf7+  . }
8. Bb5
{ White has many tempting continuations, but this move defines the structure and promises a lasting advantage.  8.b4!?  ,  8.O-O  , and  8.d3  are all interesting too. }
8... Bg4 { Black maintains his bishop on e5 by pinning the f3-knight. } 9.
Bxc6+ bxc6 10. d3 Ne7 11. O-O Qd6 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 O-O 14. Bf4
{ This structure is really favorable for White. Black needed to play more dynamically so that the a4-knight would be more problematic for us. }
*

