1. e4 e5 2. f4 Bc5
{ The Old Classical line. Black first develops the bishop to a better position, and only then plays d7-d6. }
3. Nf3
{ We are never in a hurry to capture the pawn on e5!  3.fxe5??  Qh4+-+  . }
3... d6 4. c3 Nf6 { This move is more frequent than others. } 5. d4 exd4 6.
cxd4 Bb6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. Qe2
{ Preparing Be3 and O-O-O.   9.Be3?  would be a mistake in view of  dxe5  10.fxe5  Ndxe5∓ }
9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Nc5 { Black relies on his activity. } 11. Be3 Bf5
{ The threat of ...Nd3+ forces us to give up the bishop pair. } 12. Bxc5 Bxc5
13. Rd1 Qe7 14. a3
{ Preventing Black's only counterplay.  14.Nd5  allows  14...Bb4+  . } 14...
Be6 15. f5 Bb3 16. Rd2
{ The bishop on b3 is going to be attacked quite soon and it doesn't have any retreat squares. }
16... O-O 17. Qb5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 19. Re2 Qxf5 20. Qxb3
{ The position is not so clear yet. Black has two pawns for the pieces and some play against our king in the center. Once we finish our development with g3 and Bg2, or by trading rooks on e8 followed by Be2, it should be close to winning. }
