{ You may also include  8.a5  Ba7  if you want, and then play  9.Bc4  . It shouldn't make too much of a difference. }
8... Nf6 9. d3
{ The position is very similar to those arising from the Italian Game/Giuoco Piano. }
9... O-O 10. Qe2
{ Preparing Be3. White enjoys some space advantage on the queenside which is said to be very important in the Italian game. }
10... Qd6 11. a5 Ba7 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Be6 14. Nbd2
{ This looks like a promising version of the Italian game. Black will have to work a while to completely equalize the game. For example, }
14... Rad8 15. Rd1 Nh5 16. O-O Nf4 17. Bxe6 Qxe6 18. d4 exd4
{ You should avoid  19.Qxf4  dxc3  when White is suddenly under pressure. } 19.
cxd4 Qh6 20. Kh1 f5 21. Qb3+ Kh8 22. exf5 Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Rxd4 24. Nf3 Rxd1 25.
Rxd1
{ With an equal position. White's idea is to push g3 and kick Black's active knight. }
