1. e4 e5 2. f4 d6
{ One of the calm options. The biggest threat, however, awaits us after the ingenuous  3.Nf3  . }
3. Nc3
{ 3.Nf3  exf4  would transpose toarguably the best line at Black's disposal, so it is reasonable to dodge that bullet.   On the other hand,  3.d3  is a good way to flee from the field of theoretical battle. }
3... exf4 4. Qf3
{ Almost a novelty. As you can see, White is serious about winning back a pawn! }
4... Nc6
{ Defending the pawn with  4...g5  can be met with  5.h4  Nc6  threatening Nd4.  6.d3  g4  7.Qf2!  with a slight advantage for White. }
5. Qxf4
{ 5.Bb5  doesn't promise anything in this case.  5...Bd7  6.Bxc6  Bxc6  7.Qxf4  d5=  . }
5... Nb4
{ A principled move. Another logical try is  5...Nd4  6.Bd3  Nf6  7.Nge2  Ne6  8.Qg3  g6  9.Bc4  Bg7  10.Qh4=  and it's more or less equal. White should first castle followed by d3 and perhaps Bh6 in the future. }
6. Kd1 { Our king always plays an important role! } 6... g6 7. Bb5+
{ This position is really imbalanced. Which is sort of the point, isn't it? }
7... c6 8. a3 Na6
{ 8...Nxc2?!  is not great because of  9.Bc4  d5  10.exd5  Nxa1  11.Qe5+±  and White has a clearly better position. }
9. Bxa6 bxa6 10. Nf3 Bg7 11. Rf1 Ne7 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 c5 14. Kc1
{ White should trade a pair of bishops, connect rooks and stabilize the pawn structure in order to get a serious advantage. }
