{ Defending the pawn with  4...g5  can be met with  5.h4  Nc6  threatening Nd4.  6.d3  g4  7.Qf2!  with a slight advantage for White. }
5. Qxf4
{ 5.Bb5  doesn't promise anything in this case.  5...Bd7  6.Bxc6  Bxc6  7.Qxf4  d5=  . }
5... Nb4
{ A principled move. Another logical try is  5...Nd4  6.Bd3  Nf6  7.Nge2  Ne6  8.Qg3  g6  9.Bc4  Bg7  10.Qh4=  and it's more or less equal. White should first castle followed by d3 and perhaps Bh6 in the future. }
6. Kd1 { Our king always plays an important role! } 6... c5
{ Black establishes control over d4 square. } 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. a3 Nc6
10. Nd5 Nxd5
{ Another alternative here is  10...Ne5  but now White can simplify with  11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  13.Nxe7  Qxe7  14.Nf3  and White is quite comfortable. }
11. exd5 Ne5 12. Nf3 O-O 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxd5 15. Kc1
{ White has a lot of simple improving moves, while our king will be completely safe on b2. }
*

