[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 3: 2...d6"]
[Black "3...exf4 4.Qf3 Nc6 5.Qxf4 Nb4 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d6
{ One of the calm options. The biggest threat, however, awaits us after the ingenuous  3.Nf3  . }
3. Nc3
{ 3.Nf3  exf4  would transpose toarguably the best line at Black's disposal, so it is reasonable to dodge that bullet.   On the other hand,  3.d3  is a good way to flee from the field of theoretical battle. }
3... exf4 4. Qf3
{ Almost a novelty. As you can see, White is serious about winning back a pawn! }
4... Nc6
{ Defending the pawn with  4...g5  can be met with  5.h4  Nc6  threatening Nd4.  6.d3  g4  7.Qf2!  with a slight advantage for White. }
5. Qxf4
{ 5.Bb5  doesn't promise anything in this case.  5...Bd7  6.Bxc6  Bxc6  7.Qxf4  d5=  . }
5... Nb4
{ A principled move. Another logical try is  5...Nd4  6.Bd3  Nf6  7.Nge2  Ne6  8.Qg3  g6  9.Bc4  Bg7  10.Qh4=  and it's more or less equal. White should first castle followed by d3 and perhaps Bh6 in the future. }
6. Kd1 { Our king always plays an important role! } 6... Nf6 7. Nf3 h6
{ Black wants to kick the white queen from a very sound position.  7...c5  eventually leads to a transposition  8.b3  Be7  9.Bb2  O-O   9...Be6  10.Bc4+=  .  10.a3  Nc6  11.Nd5  Nxd5  12.exd5  Ne5  13.Nxe5  dxe5  14.Bxe5  . }
8. Bc4 g5 9. Qe3 Bg7 10. h4 g4
{ It's better to keep the kingside closed. Worse is  10...Ng4  11.Qe1  gxh4  12.Rxh4  Nc6  13.d3  h5  14.Bg5  f6  15.Bd2+=  with a slight advantage. }
11. e5 { The only move but sufficient. } 11... dxe5 12. Qxe5+ Kf8
{ A very chaotic position. As usual, engines recommend us to repeat moves. }
13. Nd4 Nfd5 14. Qe4 Nf6
{ 14...Nb6  doesn't promise an easy life  15.Nde2  Nxc4  16.Qxc4  Nc6  17.Rf1+=  . }
