[White "Chapter 4: 2...Nc6"]
[Black "3...exf4 4.d4 g5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 Nc6
{ Another sideline. A fine developing move, which, however, prevents Black from capturing on f4 and therefore is not dangerous at all. }
3. Nf3 exf4
{ Not the best moment to capture on f4.   3...d6  will probably just transpose to the 2...d6 chapter. }
4. d4 g5 { This looks strange with the knight on c6. } 5. d5 g4 6. dxc6 gxf3 7.
Qxf3 Qh4+
{ Otherwise Black is in trouble: White has the better pawn structure and lead in development. }
8. g3 fxg3 9. hxg3 Qf6 { White doesn't have to trade queens straight away: }
10. Qb3 { Black has to be precise. For example, } 10... dxc6 11. Bf4 Bh6 12.
Nd2 Bxf4 13. gxf4 Qxf4 14. O-O-O Bg4 15. Ba6 { Now White is winning. } 15...
Bxd1 16. Rf1 Qh6 17. Qxf7+ Kd8 18. Bxb7
{ Qf8+ will win a full rook, for example:  18...Be2  19.Qf8+  Qxf8  20.Rxf8+  Ke7  21.Rxa8  and White is close to winning because of the pressure on the back rank. }
