[White "Chapter 5. 2...d5 - the Falkbeer Countergambit"]
[Black "3...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 c6 { This is the so-called Nimzowitsch Variation. } 4. Ne2
{ An interesting way to develop the kingside while preparing the f4-e5 capture.   4.Qe2  cxd5  5.fxe5  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Nc3  Nge7  8.d4  Nxd4  9.Qf2  Nxf3  10.gxf3  Be6  11.Bg5  is another idea. }
4... cxd5 5. fxe5 Qh4+ 6. Ng3 Nc6 7. c3 Nxe5
{ 7...d4  is insufficient bad because of  8.Bb5  Bc5  9.d3  Nge7  10.Nd2+=  with either Ne4 or Nf3 ideas. }
8. d4
{ White has easy development and potential play against the black king and/or isolated pawn. }
8... Ng4 9. Qf3 Bd6 10. Bf4 Qe7+ 11. Kd2
{ With a good position. We shouldn't be worried about putting our King in the center as queens will get exchanged very quickly in this position.  Another important note is to not play  11.Be2?  because of  11...Bxf4  12.Qxf4  Ne3  and Black wins material. }
