1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 e4
{ This is the old main line. The idea is to restrict White's knight from developing to f3. }
4. d3 { However, now White is just better. } 4... Nf6
{ People normally choose this move in comparison with  4...Qxd5  , but the position is just sad for Black here. }
5. dxe4 Nxe4 6. Nf3 Bc5 7. Qe2 Bf5
{ 7...Qe7  can be met with  8.Be3  followed by Nbd2-O-O-O and White is clearly better thanks to the extra pawn. }
8. Nc3 Qe7 9. Be3 { We just want to exchange pieces as we are up in material. }
9... Nxc3 { Simplifying the position does not help Black. } 10. Bxc5 Qxe2+ 11.
Bxe2 Nxe2 12. Kxe2 Na6 13. Ba3 Bxc2 14. Kd2 Be4 15. Ng5
{ We should be careful to not confuse the move order with  15.Rhe1?!  as after  15...f5  16.Ng5  O-O-O  Black will get some breathing space. }
15... Bxd5
{ 15...f5  does not work in this case because of  16.Nxe4  fxe4  17.Ke3  with a winning endgame. }
16. Rhe1+ Kd8 17. Re5 Bc4 18. b3 f6 19. Re7 fxg5 20. bxc4 gxf4 21. Rxg7
{ With obvious winning chances thanks to complete domination on the 7th rank and the lack of coordination between Black's pieces. }
