[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ White has a wide choice here:  5.c4  ,  5.Bc4  ,  5.Be2  ,  5.d4  and  5.Nc3  . I'd suggest to try }
5. Bb5+
{ Many famous players have tested this variation in the past. In particular, Nakamura, Zvjaginsev and Savchenko tried this move. }
5... Bd7
{ This is another continuation. White will have good chances to play for an advantage in this case. }
6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 7. O-O Qxd5 8. d4 Nc6
{ 8...Qf5  doesn't help as we can capture the pawn anyway via  9.Nh4  Qd7  10.Bxf4+=  . }
9. Bxf4 O-O-O 10. c3 Nh5
{ 10...Bd6  is also possible but after  11.Bg5  Rhe8  12.Bxf6  gxf6  13.Nbd2  Bf4  14.Kh1+=  White is slightly better thanks to Black's damaged pawn structure  . }
11. Bd2 Be7 { 11...Bd6  12.Qb3  doesn't change much  . } 12. Qb3 Rhe8 13. Na3
{ White has a slight pull. The idea should be to try and force Black to take ...Qxb3 which will guarantee us a better endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5. 2...d5 - the Falkbeer Countergambit"]
[Black "3...exf4 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bb5+ Bd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ White has a wide choice here:  5.c4  ,  5.Bc4  ,  5.Be2  ,  5.d4  and  5.Nc3  . I'd suggest to try }
5. Bb5+
{ Many famous players have tested this variation in the past. In particular, Nakamura, Zvjaginsev and Savchenko tried this move. }
5... Bd7
{ This is another continuation. White will have good chances to play for an advantage in this case. }
6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 7. O-O Nxd5 8. c4 Nb6 9. d4 Nxc4 10. Qd3 Nd6
{ Once again, a precise decision.  10...Nb6  isn't as effective because after  11.Ne5  Qe6  12.Nc3  Nc6  13.Nxc6  Qxc6  14.Bxf4  Be7  15.Rae1→  Black will have practical problems. }
11. Bxf4 Be7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Ne5 Qd8 14. Nd5 Nd7
{ 14...Nc6  is also logical but after  15.Rae1  Nxe5  16.Rxe5  we will transpose to the main variation. }
15. Rae1 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Re8 17. Rh5 g6 18. Rh3
{ The calm retreat. We don't need to be super tactical here because Black has committed g6 and therefore has long-term problems pertaining to the dark squares.   A more direct approach here is  18.Be5  but, unfortunately, it ends with an equal position after  18...gxh5  19.Qg3+  Bg5  20.Nf6+  Qxf6  21.Rxf6  Ne4  22.Qf3  Bxf6  23.Bxf6  Nxf6  24.Qxf6  Re6  25.Qg5+=  . }
18... Qd7 19. Be5
{ It must be scary to play this with Black, but somehow computer shows equality. }
*

