[White "Chapter 5. 2...d5 - the Falkbeer Countergambit"]
[Black "3...exf4 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bb5+ Nbd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ White has a wide choice here:  5.c4  ,  5.Bc4  ,  5.Be2  ,  5.d4  and  5.Nc3  . I'd suggest to try }
5. Bb5+
{ Many famous players have tested this variation in the past. In particular, Nakamura, Zvjaginsev and Savchenko tried this move. }
5... Nbd7 { Is seen rarely in practice. White already has a good position. } 6.
O-O Be7 7. Be2
{ Black made a couple of passive moves, so we can step back with our bishop a little. }
7... Nxd5 { And now we go for the same idea with } 8. c4 N5f6 9. d4
{ Threatening to take the pawn and develop at the same time. } 9... O-O 10. Nc3
Re8 11. Bxf4 Nf8 12. Bg3
{ With a comfortable position. White will retain a small edge here because of space and central control, not to mention our superior coordination of pieces. }
