[White "Chapter 5. 2...d5 - the Falkbeer Countergambit"]
[Black "3...exf4 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bb5+ c6 6.dxc6 bxc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ White has a wide choice here:  5.c4  ,  5.Bc4  ,  5.Be2  ,  5.d4  and  5.Nc3  . I'd suggest to try }
5. Bb5+
{ Many famous players have tested this variation in the past. In particular, Nakamura, Zvjaginsev and Savchenko tried this move. }
5... c6 { The main continuation. } 6. dxc6 bxc6
{ A little bit strange move, which, nevertheless, is somewhat popular. } 7. Bc4
{ White is doing quite good here. } 7... Nd5 { Makes little sense. } 8. Nc3
{ Simple developing move with a prophylactic purpose, we don't want to allow Black's bishop to develop to its ideal square on d6 anymore. }
8... Be6 9. Qe2
{ Once again, our idea is to not allow  ...Bd6  and of course to put further pressure on the knight.  9.O-O??  loses the piece immediately via  9...Nxc3  . }
9... Be7 10. Nd4 { Wasting no time! } 10... Nxc3 11. dxc3 Bxc4 12. Qxc4
{ White seems to be almost winning here. But black has one resource: } 12...
Bh4+
{ The point of all the exchanges. But we are fine here anyway thanks to a sneaky intermezzo. }
13. g3 fxg3 14. Qe2+ { The intermezzo. White is now clearly better. } 14... Qe7
{ If Black does not choose to exchange the queens and instead goes for  14...Kf8  we can simply play  15.O-O  and the kingside attack is too dangerous. }
15. Qxe7+ Bxe7 16. hxg3
{ With a clearly better endgame. Our idea here is to, first, develop our pieces and O-O-O. Second, we want to put pressure on the c6-pawn in the long run. }
*

