[Black "3...exf4 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bb5+ c6 6.dxc6 Nxc6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ White has a wide choice here:  5.c4  ,  5.Bc4  ,  5.Be2  ,  5.d4  and  5.Nc3  . I'd suggest to try }
5. Bb5+
{ Many famous players have tested this variation in the past. In particular, Nakamura, Zvjaginsev and Savchenko tried this move. }
5... c6 { The main continuation. } 6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. Nc3 Qb6
{ Interesting choice. Black is in no hurry to decide on squares for bishops. }
8. a4 Be7 9. d4
{ A double-edged position arises. We have another alternative here  9.a5  Qc7  10.O-O  O-O  11.d4  Rd8  12.Ne2  Bd6  13.c3  a6  14.Bd3  h6  15.Qe1∞  with an unclear game ahead. We have attacking chances on the kingside starting with Qh4. }
9... O-O 10. O-O Bg4 11. Ne2 a6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. h3 Bf5
{ Probably the best response. Black should avoid simplifying the position too quickly. As we see in this variation:  13...Bxf3  14.Rxf3  c5  15.a5  Qb7  16.Bxf4  where White is quite comfortable . }
14. a5 Qb7 15. Nxf4
{ We are a pawn up, but the position is far from clear. Black has a double bishop advantage and more active pieces at the moment, which is sufficient compensation for the pawn.   Our next few moves are pretty simple: Nd3 @@StartBracket@@to protect b2@@EndBracket@@ followed by either Be3 or Bf4. In the long run, we should aim to exchange pieces to simplify matters. }
