{ Interesting idea. We are aiming to pose problems early on with Nd4 or Ng5 ideas. Black has plenty of decent moves here. I'll show some options to illuminate the alleged course of the game. }
8... Bc5 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Ng5 O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. b3 Nd5 13. Bb2 Qh4+ 14. g3
{ Vital intermezzo, yet again! } 14... Qf6
{ 14...fxg3  once again is not a good move because of  15.O-O-O  Nf4  16.Qe1!  Bf2  17.hxg3  Qxg3  18.Qe4→  with tremendous attacking possibilities. }
15. O-O-O f3 16. Qc4 Bd4 17. Rhf1 f2 18. Kb1
{ With a so-called dynamic equality. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5. 2...d5 - the Falkbeer Countergambit"]
[Black "3...exf4 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bb5+ c6 6.dxc6 Nxc6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5
{ The Falkbeer Countergambit is a fair and time-tested way to handle the King's Gambit. }
3. exd5 exf4 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ White has a wide choice here:  5.c4  ,  5.Bc4  ,  5.Be2  ,  5.d4  and  5.Nc3  . I'd suggest to try }
5. Bb5+
{ Many famous players have tested this variation in the past. In particular, Nakamura, Zvjaginsev and Savchenko tried this move. }
5... c6 { The main continuation. } 6. dxc6 Nxc6 7. Nc3 Be6
{ An accurate reaction.   7...Bb4  is also possible but after  8.d4  O-O  9.O-O  Bd6  10.Ne2  Nh5  11.c4⇆  we reach a similar position with an extra tempo as Black played Bb4-Bd6. }
8. Qe2
{ Interesting idea. We are aiming to pose problems early on with Nd4 or Ng5 ideas. Black has plenty of decent moves here. I'll show some options to illuminate the alleged course of the game. }
8... Qb6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. b3 Bb4
{ 10...Bd6  11.Na4  Qb5  12.Bb2  brings a good position. As mentioned earlier, we should not be afraid to exchange queens in this variation because of Black's weak pawn structure. }
11. Na4 Qd8 12. Ng5 O-O 13. Nxe6 Qd6 14. Bb2 Rae8 15. O-O-O Rxe6 16. Qf3 Rfe8
17. Rhf1
{ With an equal position. We should remember to answer ...Re2 with Rf2 always and to not give our opponent the mighty 7th rank! }
*

