1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4
{ 'The refutation of any gambit begins with accepting it. In my opinion the King's Gambit is busted. It loses by force.' - R. Fischer, A Bust to the King's Gambit. }
3. Nf3 d6
{ The best move according to Stockfish and Robert James Fischer. Calling this move the refutation is still an exaggeration, but I'd say this is the line with the least fun for White. }
4. Bc4 { White anticipates the ...g5-move. } 4... g5
{ Leads to drawish positions with minor chances for White. } 5. h4 h6 6. hxg5
Bg7 7. gxh6 Rxh6 8. Rxh6 Bxh6
{ Surprisingly, despite the material is equal and White's stronger center, Black is right in time with his response. }
9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qe2 Bg4 11. Qf2 Bg7
{ Black is in time to prevent d4 and create counterplay. } 12. Bb3
{ Preparing Ne2 and d4 as an extra option, but after the precise } 12... a5
{ The knight is tied to the c3-square @@StartBracket@@to prevent ...a4, trapping our bishop@@EndBracket@@. }
13. d3
{ 13.a3  or  13.a4  would leave the b3-bishop vulnerable to ...Nd4-Nxb3 ideas. }
13... Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qf6 15. Bd2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 a4 17. Bd5 Nge7
{ White can't maintain the bishop pair. } 18. O-O-O
{ The position is playable. There are only pawns on the queenside left, because even the pawn@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@ on e4 and on the f-file could be said to be part of the same pawn island in this pawn structure. This makes it difficult for White to create any realistic winning chances. }
