[Black "4.Bc4 h6 5.h4 Be6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4
{ 'The refutation of any gambit begins with accepting it. In my opinion the King's Gambit is busted. It loses by force.' - R. Fischer, A Bust to the King's Gambit. }
3. Nf3 d6
{ The best move according to Stockfish and Robert James Fischer. Calling this move the refutation is still an exaggeration, but I'd say this is the line with the least fun for White. }
4. Bc4 { White anticipates the ...g5-move. } 4... h6
{ Black prepares ...g7-g5. } 5. h4
{ It's important to prevent ...g7-g5: if Black could play this move unpunished, his position will be completely fine. }
5... Be6 { With h4 & h6 inclusion this move becomes more sensible. } 6. Qe2
{ Kingside castling isn't an option anymore, so White prepares castling queenside. }
6... Nc6 7. Nc3 Bg4
{ Pretentious but sensible attempt: ...Nd4 comes with tempo and White has no d2-d4. }
8. Qf2 Nf6 9. d4 Qe7
{ It's hard to hang on to the e4-pawn, so we simply sacrifice it and play for development. }
10. O-O Bxf3 11. Nd5
{ 11.Qxf3  loses the d4-pawn while  11.gxf3  weakens our kingside too much. }
11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Be4 13. dxc6 bxc6 14. Bxf4 f5
{ This bishop is called to shield Black from trouble. } 15. d5
{ White complicates the position even more. He may not allow Black to set up a blockade with ...d5. }
15... cxd5 16. Bb5+ Kd8 17. Bc6 Rc8 18. Rae1
{ White is two pawns down, but he is very active and it's not easy for Black to untangle. I would enjoy playing this position from the White side, even though it's highly unclear. }
*

