{ 'The refutation of any gambit begins with accepting it. In my opinion the King's Gambit is busted. It loses by force.' - R. Fischer, A Bust to the King's Gambit. }
3. Nf3 d6
{ The best move according to Stockfish and Robert James Fischer. Calling this move the refutation is still an exaggeration, but I'd say this is the line with the least fun for White. }
4. Bc4 { White anticipates the ...g5-move. } 4... h6
{ Black prepares ...g7-g5. } 5. h4
{ It's important to prevent ...g7-g5: if Black could play this move unpunished, his position will be completely fine. }
5... Nf6
{ This move is the strongest along with  5...Nc6  , which will tend to transpose anyway, but basically every logical move is decent for Black.   5...c6  6.Nc3  Nf6  transposes to our line.   5...Bg4  6.d4  Be7  transposes to 4.Bc4 h6 5.h4 Be7. }
6. Nc3 Be7 { Black can also try to put pressure on the h4-pawn this way. } 7.
d4 Nh5 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. Bxf4 Bg4 10. O-O { We can't save the h4-pawn - as usual. }
