1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4
{ 'The refutation of any gambit begins with accepting it. In my opinion the King's Gambit is busted. It loses by force.' - R. Fischer, A Bust to the King's Gambit. }
3. Nf3 d6
{ The best move according to Stockfish and Robert James Fischer. Calling this move the refutation is still an exaggeration, but I'd say this is the line with the least fun for White. }
4. Bc4 { White anticipates the ...g5-move. } 4... h6
{ Black prepares ...g7-g5. } 5. h4
{ It's important to prevent ...g7-g5: if Black could play this move unpunished, his position will be completely fine. }
5... Nf6
{ This move is the strongest along with  5...Nc6  , which will tend to transpose anyway, but basically every logical move is decent for Black.   5...c6  6.Nc3  Nf6  transposes to our line.   5...Bg4  6.d4  Be7  transposes to 4.Bc4 h6 5.h4 Be7. }
6. Nc3 Nc6 7. d4 Nh5
{ Perhaps this is the most unpleasant line, and here White is really forced to struggle for an equality. }
8. Nd5 Ng3 9. Rh2 { I can't guarantee your safety after  9.Rg1  . } 9... Ne7
{ This is the move order that really tests White.  9...Nxe4?  10.Qe2+-  followed by Bxf4 and O-O-O is the dream of every King's Gambit player. }
10. Nxf4 Nxe4 11. Qe2 d5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxe4+ Be6
{ The material is equal, but Black has active pieces and no weaknesses. A draw will be our pleasure. }
14. Bd2 Bd6 15. Bxd5
{ Alas, there is nothing better than agreeing to an unpleasant endgame. } 15...
Bg3+ 16. Kf1 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 Bxd5 18. Rh3 Bd6
{ Smoke cleared. Black has two bishops, but White is fortunately in time with the adequate counterplay. }
19. Re1+ Kd8 20. Ne5 f6 21. Nd3 Re8 22. b3
{ Preparing c2-c4. White wants to trade off one of the bishops with Nf4 or Bf4.   Play could continue:  22...Kd7  23.c4  Rxe1+  24.Bxe1  Be6  25.Re3  Bf5  26.Nc5+  Bxc5  27.dxc5=  Black is slightly better, but the game is extremely likely to end in a draw because of the opposite-colored bishops. }
*

