[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: King's Gambit Accepted - 3...g5"]
[Black "4...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4
{ Congratulations! You've finally reached the most annoying move, the last boss -  2...exf4  . Frankly speaking, difficulties are yet to come... }
3. Nf3 g5
{ This move is thought to be the official refutation of the King's Gambit, it is also the recommendation of GM Sethuraman in his 1...e5 course here on Chessable. It poses serious problems indeed, but analysis shows that White is @@StartBracket@@almost@@EndBracket@@ OK here. Black has couple of new interesting tries, but all of them lead to some huge complications. }
4. h4
{ We can also gamble with  4.Bc4  ,  4.d4  or even  4.Nc3  , but with precise play Black will eventually extinguish our initiative. }
4... d5
{ Almost no one played like this, but it's an interesting move which deserves serious attention. }
5. d4 { Development first. } 5... dxe4 6. Nxg5 Nf6
{ If Black tries to be greedy with  6...e3  then we respond with  7.Bc4  followed by castle. }
7. Nc3
{ Unfortunately  7.Bc4  does not work in this case as Black can respond with  7...Bg4!  . }
7... Bb4 8. Bxf4 h6 9. Bc4
{ The knight was a lost cause anyway, as this is a typical theme in the King's Gambit. }
9... hxg5 10. Bxg5
{ We can already see the compensation for the sacrificed piece. Few engine lines would help to understand what's going on: }
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qd6 { Getting out of the dreaded pin. } 12. O-O Nd5 13.
Qe1 Nc6
{ Black can also try the logical  13...f5  where we go all in with  14.g4!  The position is still quite complicated. However, practically Black will struggle to defend. }
14. Qxe4+ Be6 15. Qd3
{ We are not in a rush. The idea is to protect our pawn on c3 and slowly improve with Bb3-c4. }
15... Kd7
{ Black is forcing us to take the knight with this move. As we shall see: } 16.
Bxd5
{ Unfortunately  16.Bb3  does not work in this case as Black can carry out the plan with  16...Rag8  17.c4  Rxg5!  with a winning position. }
16... Qxd5 17. c4 Qxc4 18. d5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5+ Bxd5 20. Rad1
{ We have recovered our sacrificed piece, or have we? } 20... Ke6 21. g4
{ Now we can happily give a perpetual with Rf6-Rf5+.  21...Rag8  22.Rf6+  Ke5  23.Rf5+  Ke6  24.Rf6+= }
*

