{ Congratulations! You've finally reached the most annoying move, the last boss -  2...exf4  . Frankly speaking, difficulties are yet to come... }
3. Nf3 g5
{ This move is thought to be the official refutation of the King's Gambit, it is also the recommendation of GM Sethuraman in his 1...e5 course here on Chessable. It poses serious problems indeed, but analysis shows that White is @@StartBracket@@almost@@EndBracket@@ OK here. Black has couple of new interesting tries, but all of them lead to some huge complications. }
4. h4
{ We can also gamble with  4.Bc4  ,  4.d4  or even  4.Nc3  , but with precise play Black will eventually extinguish our initiative. }
4... g4 5. Ne5 d6 { Also a very important line. } 6. Nxg4 Nc6 7. Nf2 Nf6 8. d4
Bh6 9. Be2 Qe7
{ It's important to meet  9...Rg8  with  10.Bf3  .   Note that  10.O-O  allows  10...f3!  11.Bxf3  Bxc1  12.Qxc1  Nxd4  . }
10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Nd5
{ 11.a3!?  would be a great idea, but after  11...O-O-O  12.Qd3  Kb8  13.Bd2  Black has  Be6!  14.O-O-O  d5=+  . }
11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Nb4 13. c4
{ I honestly have no idea what's going on, but the computer shows equality in every sensible variation. }
13... Bf5 14. O-O Nc2 15. Bd3 Bxd3
{ 15...Ne3  is quite harmless as after  16.Bxe3  fxe3  17.Ng4  e2  18.Qxe2  Qxe2  19.Nf6+  Ke7  20.Bxe2  Kxf6  21.Bg4  we maintain a small edge. Although with correct play Black can equalise. }
16. Nxd3 Ne3 17. Bxe3 Qxe3+
{ 17...fxe3  allows  18.Qg4  and White suddenly has an almost winning position. }
18. Kh1 O-O-O
{ Black should not be greedy with  18...Qxd4  because now Black wont be able to castle.  19.Qe2+  Qe3  20.Qh5!  Qxd3  21.Rae1+  with a great position. }
19. Nxf4 Rde8 20. Qh5 Bxf4 21. Qf5+ Kb8 22. Qxf4
{ We have an extra pawn, but Black's activity compensates for that. } *

