Nxe4 { 6...d6  transposes to 5...d6 6.Nxg4 Nf6. } 7. d3 Ng3 8. Bxf4
{ Our main idea. } 8... Nxh1 { An important forced line. } 9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. Nf6+
Kd8 11. Bxc7+ Kxc7 12. Nd5+ Kd8 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. Qf3 Bxh4+ 15. Kd2
{ Material balance is irretrievably violated. Black has two light pieces and a rook for a queen, but its forces are too disunited. It's nearly impossible to cover all the opportunities which both sides have, so let's check few sample lines. }
15... Bg5+ 16. Kc3 Nc6 17. Na3 Be7 18. b4 Rg8
{ Black should not take the bait with  18...Bxb4+  as after  19.Kb2  Rg8  20.g4  the knight on h1 is dead. }
19. g4 Ng3 { 19...Bxb4+  will transpose after  20.Kb2  . } 20. Qxg3 Bf6+ 21.
Kd2 Bxa1 22. c3
{ With a slight advantage for us thanks to the weakened dark squares in Black's territory combined with passive coordination of pieces. }
