[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: King's Gambit Accepted - 3...Nf6"]
[Black "4...Nd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ One of the modern ways to fight the King's Gambit and recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable. Black doesn't want to mess with all sorts of ...g7-g5 ideas and plays for development instead. }
4. e5
{ Probably forced, as  4.Nc3  allows Black to illustrate one of the ideas behind the 3rd move, by playing  4...d5  with an easy game. }
4... Nd5 { Pours water into our mill, on d5 the knight is vulnerable. } 5. Nc3
Nxc3 6. dxc3
{ Perhaps a puzzling decision for players who are starting out learning the game. Don't we always capture towards the centre to increase our influence in it? Here development is more important, and  6.bxc3  d6  would give Black an easy game. By capturing with the d-pawn, White is ready to capture on f4 on the next game. }
6... d5 7. Bxf4 Be7 8. Qd2
{ White has a clear advantage and will prepare queenside castling next. Our king is very safe on c1, because of the 4 pawns covering it, and the rook appearing on d1 will add additional pressure on the d5-pawn. Another typical idea will be to launch our h-pawn forward, creating discomfort on the kingside where it is likely Black's king will end up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: King's Gambit Accepted - 3...Nf6"]
[Black "4...Nd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ One of the modern ways to fight the King's Gambit and recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable. Black doesn't want to mess with all sorts of ...g7-g5 ideas and plays for development instead. }
4. e5
{ Probably forced, as  4.Nc3  allows Black to illustrate one of the ideas behind the 3rd move, by playing  4...d5  with an easy game. }
4... Nd5 { Pours water into our mill, on d5 the knight is vulnerable. } 5. Nc3
c6 { Black's setup looks very artificial. } 6. Nxd5 cxd5 7. d4
{ It's already obvious White is doing more than OK, but it's never a bad idea to check few sample lines: }
7... g5 { 7...d6  8.Bxf4  gives White a large advantage in development. } 8. h4
g4 9. Ng5
{ In keeping with the spirit of King's Gambit, the knight is headed for f7! }
9... h6 10. Nxf7 { Of course! } 10... Kxf7 11. Qxg4 d6 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. Bxf4
{ A typical position for the opening we are discussing. Black will have a tough time facing the long-term initiative that White has. White intends to castle queenside and bring the a1-rook into the game via d1-d3 to g3. It is very hard for Black to counter that plan. }
*

