1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ One of the modern ways to fight the King's Gambit and recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable. Black doesn't want to mess with all sorts of ...g7-g5 ideas and plays for development instead. }
4. e5
{ Probably forced, as  4.Nc3  allows Black to illustrate one of the ideas behind the 3rd move, by playing  4...d5  with an easy game. }
4... Ne4 { A reasonable move for those aiming for a solid game. } 5. d3
{ Immediately hitting the knight. } 5... Ng5
{ 5...Nc5  6.d4  would costs Black additional time. } 6. Bxf4
{ Having won back our sacrificed pawn, including a small lead in development, we can already be satisfied with the outcome of the opening. Having said that, }
6... Ne6 7. Be3 c5
{ Is a worthy try to prevent d3-d4, and keeps White's advantage to a minimum. }
8. Nc3 { 8.d4?!  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Qa5+  is followed by capture on e5. } 8... Nc6
9. g3
{ Preparing to develop the bishop on the long diagonal, where it is much more effective than on e2. }
9... d5 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O
{ This looks more like a position from the King's Indian Defence and is approximately equal. White can continue with moves like Qd2, Rae1 and perhaps even Nh4-f5. }
