[White "Chapter 9: King's Gambit Accepted - 3...Nf6"]
[Black "4...Nh5 5.d4 d5 6.c4 g5 7.g4 Ng7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ One of the modern ways to fight the King's Gambit and recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable. Black doesn't want to mess with all sorts of ...g7-g5 ideas and plays for development instead. }
4. e5
{ Probably forced, as  4.Nc3  allows Black to illustrate one of the ideas behind the 3rd move, by playing  4...d5  with an easy game. }
4... Nh5
{ Famously, a knight on the rim is dim... or is it? From h5 the knight simply keeps the pawn on f4 alive and challenges White to prove compensation. }
5. d4
{ The move I recommend, we take the centre and support our e5-pawn. Magnus Carlsen tried  5.Qe2  but was slightly worse after  5...Be7  6.d4  O-O  7.Nc3  d6  preparing ...Bc8-g4 as seen in Carlsen, M. - Ding Liren, Chess24.com rapid 2020. Ding went on to win that game in straightforward fashion. }
5... d5 { Krishnan Sasikiran used to play like this in the 2000s. } 6. c4
{ We have to strike swiftly. } 6... g5 7. g4
{ It turns out that capturing the brave pawn is not good at all,  7...fxg3  8.Nxg5!  and Black's position is collapsing. Mind-boggling complications are ahead. Just enjoy the chaos! }
7... Ng7 8. Nc3
{ Not just a simple developing move, but one that adds additional pressure to the important d5-square. }
8... c6 { Giving support to the d5-pawn. } 9. h4
{ We see that with every move White tries to destabilize Black's position. Having sacrificed a pawn there must always be a sense of urgency in our play. Black can't be allowed to simply finish development and enjoy the extra pawn! }
9... Bxg4 10. Be2 Bb4 11. Bd2 { Setting a nice trap! } 11... Nf5
{ A strong looking knight move. The threat is to jump to g3 which looks hard to face. }
12. Nxg5 { This is the trap, Black is suddenly busted. } 12... Bxe2 13. Qxe2
Ng3 14. Qg4 Nxh1 15. Nxf7 { Easy to miss from afar. } 15... Kxf7 16. e6+ Ke7
{ Loses beautifully.  16...Kf6  17.Bxf4  isn't saving Black either. } 17. Nxd5+
cxd5 18. Bxb4+ Kf6 { 18...Ke8  19.Qh5  is mate! } 19. Kd2
{ Bringing the a1-rook into the game. White doesn't have many pieces left, but it is enough to mate the lone black king! }
