1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ One of the modern ways to fight the King's Gambit and recommended by Jan Gustafsson in his Lifetime Repertoire here on Chessable. Black doesn't want to mess with all sorts of ...g7-g5 ideas and plays for development instead. }
4. e5
{ Probably forced, as  4.Nc3  allows Black to illustrate one of the ideas behind the 3rd move, by playing  4...d5  with an easy game. }
4... Nh5
{ Famously, a knight on the rim is dim... or is it? From h5 the knight simply keeps the pawn on f4 alive and challenges White to prove compensation. }
5. d4
{ The move I recommend, we take the centre and support our e5-pawn. Magnus Carlsen tried  5.Qe2  but was slightly worse after  5...Be7  6.d4  O-O  7.Nc3  d6  preparing ...Bc8-g4 as seen in Carlsen, M. - Ding Liren, Chess24.com rapid 2020. Ding went on to win that game in straightforward fashion. }
5... d6 6. Qe2 dxe5 7. Nxe5 { A curious forced line begins here. } 7... Qh4+
{ Black needs to accept the challenge, there is simply no viable alternative. }
8. g3 { 8.Kd1  Be7  doesn't lead anywhere. Our king is quite awkward on d1. }
8... Nxg3 9. hxg3 Qxh1 10. Bxf4
{ This is not the time to get greedy. After  10.Ng6+  Be6  11.Nxh8  White is a piece up, but will soon get overrun after  11...Nc6  followed by castles queenside. The king on e1 will be feeling the heat soon. }
10... Bd6 11. Nc3
{ Here too,  11.Ng6+  Be6  12.Nxh8  Bxf4  13.gxf4  Nc6  followed by O-O-O is plain bad for White. }
11... O-O 12. O-O-O Bh3
{ Black can bail out with  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  Bh3  when White has nothing better but to play  14.Ne4  Nc6  15.Nf6+!  gxf6  16.Qh5  Bg2  17.Qg4+  Kh8  18.Qf5  and Black has nothing better but to repeat with  18...Kg8  19.Qg4+  with a draw. }
13. Nxf7 Bxf4+ 14. gxf4 Nd7 { Very precise. } 15. Qc4
