[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "LCZero vs. Stockfish, TCEC 19 Superfinal, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The King's Gambit was also tested in the top engines battles. Weird opening desicions are punished in a remarkably stylish way! }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 Qf6
{ One of the very strange variations, which was not mentioned in the course. }
3. Nf3 { After this precise move, Black already has a difficult position. }
3... d6 { 3...Qxf4  4.Nc3  Qf6  5.Bc4± } 4. Nc3 exf4 5. Nd5 Qd8 6. Nxf4 Nf6 7.
d4 { White is not afraid to sacrifice a pawn for a few tempi. } 7... Nxe4 8.
Bd3 Nf6 9. O-O Be7 10. Ng5 O-O 11. Qf3 h6 12. Ne4 Nbd7 13. Ng3
{ We don't want to exchange pieces while attacking unless we can profit from it directly. }
13... Nb6 14. b3 Bg4 15. Qf2 d5 16. h3 Bd7 17. c4 c5 18. a4
{ This move helps us to start a very important plan! } 18... dxc4 19. bxc4 Nxa4
20. d5 b5 21. Ra3
{ Our idea becomes clear. Bishop retreats to b1 to be joined by the queen from f2. Our rook will be placed perfectly on f3 or g3. }
21... Qc7 22. Bb1 Rab8 23. Re3 Bd6 24. Qc2 bxc4 25. Ngh5
{ White's attack has reached its peak, position is absolutely winning and the logical result is inevitable. }
25... Rxb1 26. Nxf6+ gxf6 27. Nh5 f5 28. Qxb1 Be5 29. Rxe5 Qxe5 30. Bf4 Qd4+
31. Kh2 Nc3 32. Qb7 Nxd5 33. Qxd5 Qxd5 34. Nf6+ Kg7 35. Nxd5 Re8 36. Rf3 Re6
37. Rg3+ Rg6 38. Ra3 a6 39. Be3 Rd6 40. Nf4 Rc6 41. Kg1 Kh7 42. Kh2 Kg7 43. h4
Be8 44. Rc3 Rc8 45. Rxc4 a5 46. Rc3 a4 47. Nd5 f6 48. Ne7 Ra8 49. Bxc5 Bd7 50.
Ba3 Ra7 51. h5 f4 52. Nd5 Kf7 53. Nxf4 Rb7 54. Rc4 Ra7 55. Rd4 Bb5 56. Rd6 Ra6
57. Rd8 Be8 58. Ng6 Bc6 59. g4 Ra5 60. Bb2 Ke6 61. Rf8 Bb5 62. Rxf6+ Kd7 63.
Ne5+ Kc8 64. Rxh6 a3 65. Rh8+ Kc7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Ivanchuk, Vasyl vs. Leko, Peter, Legends of Chess Prelim Rapid, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ Vasyl Mykhaylovych Ivanchuk is a real genius and also a walking chess encyclopedia. Even when he needed to confuse a famous chess theorist such as Peter Leko, he resorted to the King’s Gambit. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 h6 4. d4 g5 5. g3 fxg3 6. hxg3 Bg7 7. Nc3 d6 8. Be3
Nf6 9. Qd2 Ng4 10. Bg1
{ 10.O-O-O  is correct as we have learned in the relevant section! } 10... Nc6
11. O-O-O O-O 12. Nh2
{ With a sound idea to disturb the cementing position of the black knight. The main weakness of the black king position is the h6-pawn, and our plan is to get to it. }
12... Nxh2
{ Leko did not feel the danger. Had Black avoided the exchange with  12...Nf6  it would have been very difficult for White to organize an attack. }
13. Rxh2 Bg4 14. Re1 Ne7 15. Bg2
{ The idea here is that White's rook will not be disturbed on the h1 square with Bf3. But this is superfluous since with a rook on h1 we are always ready to capture on h6.   15.Bd3!  Qd7  16.Be3  and White's attack is not easy to repel. The idea of ​​e5 and Bg5 works everywhere. }
15... Qd7 16. Be3 Ng6
{ Now Black can't defend h6-pawn with his queen.   16...Rae8!  17.Reh1  Qe6  and due to the unfortunate position of the bishop, White's attack is not easy to develop. }
17. Reh1 c6 18. Rxh6 Bxh6 19. Rxh6 Kg7 20. Bxg5 f6 21. Be3 Rh8 22. b3 Rxh6 23.
Bxh6+ Kh7 24. Bf1 { Finally the bishop returns to the perfect square. } 24...
Bh3 25. Be2 Re8 26. Kb2 b5 27. Bd3
{ Objectively, everything is not so bad for black, but it is very difficult to play under the constant pressure, and black begins to make mistakes. }
27... Qg4 28. Be3 b4 { 28...Qxg3  29.e5  dxe5  30.Ne4  Qf3  31.Bg5± } 29. Nd1
Qxg3 30. Qxb4 Bg4 31. e5 { Nice punch! } 31... f5
{ 31...Bxd1  32.Qb7+  Kh8   32...Kg8  33.exf6+-  33.Qxc6!  Rg8  34.Qh1+  Qh4  35.Qxd1+- }
32. Qxd6 Bxd1 33. Bxf5 Rg8 34. Bd2
{ A quiet move that exposes all the shortcomings of Black's position. Despite the extra rook, their pieces are constrained, and White, combining attack with pushing pawns on the queenside, should win easily. }
34... Bg4 35. Qe7+ { Apparently Black blundered this. } 35... Rg7 36. Qg5 Qh2
37. Bxg4 Ne7 38. Qh5+ Qxh5 39. Bxh5 Rg2 40. Bb4 Nd5 41. Bf3 Rf2 42. Bxd5 cxd5
43. Bc5 a6 44. b4 Kg6 45. a4 Kf5 46. b5 axb5 47. axb5 Ke6 48. b6 Kd7 49. Kb3
Kc6 50. c4 dxc4+ 51. Kxc4 Rf4 52. e6 Re4 53. e7 Kd7 54. b7 Kc7 55. Bd6+ Kxb7
56. Be5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Anderssen, Adolf vs. Kieseritzky, Lionel"]
[Result "*"]

{ Obviously the most famous game played in the King's Gambit. } 1. e4 e5 2. f4
exf4 3. Bc4 Qh4+ 4. Kf1 b5 5. Bxb5 Nf6 6. Nf3 Qh6 7. d3 Nh5
{ Up to this moment, boths sides played well, but here Black could not resist to set a simple trap. }
8. Nh4 { 8.Rg1  c6  9.Bc4±  and g4-g5 grants White huge advantage. } 8... Qg5
9. Nf5
{ After an exchange of pleasantries, the position remained very complex. } 9...
c6 { 9...g6  10.h4  Qf6  11.Nc3  c6  12.Ba4∞ } 10. g4
{ Objectively not the best move, but Anderssen foresaw the beautiful idea. }
10... Nf6
{ 10...g6  11.gxh5  gxf5  12.Rg1  Qh4  13.Qf3  cxb5  14.exf5  b4!  The first line the computer gives looks roughly like this and the last move just leaves me speechless. }
11. Rg1 cxb5
{ 11...h5  12.h4  Qg6  13.g5  Ng4  14.Ba4∞  was the last chance to complicate the fight. }
12. h4 Qg6 13. h5 Qg5 14. Qf3 Ng8 15. Bxf4 Qf6 16. Nc3 Bc5 17. Nd5
{ White is obviously dominating. } 17... Qxb2 18. Bd6
{ ?!! White misses the victory, but this move is an introduction to an incredibly beautiful checkmate combination. }
18... Bxg1
{ 18...Qxa1+  19.Ke2  Qb2!  20.Bxc5  Qxc2+  21.Kf1  Qxc5  22.d4  and even here, having an extra rook and piece, Black should be very careful not to lose quickly. }
19. e5 { Black is defenseless. } 19... Qxa1+ 20. Ke2 Na6 21. Nxg7+ Kd8 22. Qf6+
Nxf6 23. Be7# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Ivanchuk, Vasyl vs. Giri, Anish, Beijing Sportacord Rapid, 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ The second jewel from the work of Vasyl Mykhaylovych. It's amazing how easily he managed to achieve this victory against such a famous theoretician and strong chess player as Anish Giri. }
1... e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bb3 d5 6. exd5 cxd5 7. d4 Bd6 8.
Nge2 f3 { Very unfortunate move. } 9. gxf3 O-O 10. Bg5
{ White's play develops by itself, which Ivanchuk uses masterly. } 10... Be6
11. Qd2 Be7 12. O-O-O Nc6 13. Nf4 Na5 14. Rhe1
{ Forcing Black to capture on b3. } 14... Nxb3+ { 14...Qd6  15.Bxd5+- } 15.
axb3 h6 16. Bh4 Qa5 17. Kb1
{ So, with very natural moves, Vasyl Mykhaylovych managed to get an absolutely winning position. }
17... Ne4 18. fxe4 Bxh4 19. Rg1 Bg5 20. h4
{ Removing the last obstacle before a direct attack. } 20... Bxf4 21. Qxf4 Kh8
22. exd5 Bd7 23. Rxg7 Kxg7 24. Rg1+ Kh7 25. Ne4 f6 26. Nxf6+ Rxf6 27. Qxf6 Bg4
28. Qe7+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Zvjaginsev, Vadim vs. Tomashevsky, Evgeny, Russian Cup Serpukhov, 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Vadim Zvjaginsev is known as a very unconventional player who likes to start creating right from the opening. And the King's Gambit helped him to score beautiful victories more than once. }
1... e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 d6 4. d4 g5 5. Nc3 Nc6
{ Possible move, but  5...g4!  is stronger:  6.Bxf4  gxf3  7.Qxf3  Nc6  8.Bb5  White has insufficient compensation. The initiative has yet to be proven. }
6. g3 g4
{ A bold decision. Black goes for a fairly stereotypical structure, in which White is clearly ahead in development and Black needs to play very accurately in order to get into a bad position.  As you might have learnt from the course, the correct move is   6...Bg7  7.d5  Ne5  8.gxf4  gxf4  9.Bxf4  Bg4  10.Be2  Bxf3  11.Bxf3  Qf6  12.Bxe5  Qxe5=+ }
7. Nh4 f3 8. Be3 Nge7
{ The beginning of Black's troubles.   8...Nf6  9.Bd3  Be7  10.a3  Nh5  11.Nxf3  gxf3  12.Qxf3  Ng7  13.O-O-O  Bg5  14.Kb1  O-O  15.Nd5  Compensation is obvious, but Black is still able to fight back. }
9. h3 Bg7 10. Qd2 d5 { Black opens the center without decent development. } 11.
O-O-O dxe4 12. d5 Ne5 13. Nxe4 { White has reached a dream position. } 13... f5
14. Bb5+ Bd7
{ 14...Kf8  15.d6  fxe4  16.dxe7+  Qxe7  17.Bg5  Bf6  18.Bxf6  Qxf6  19.Rhe1  could have prolonged the resistance, but the result of the game would hardly have changed. }
15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Ng5 Nf8 17. Bc5 Bf6 18. Rhe1 f2 19. Bxf2 Rg8 20. Ne6 Nxe6
21. Rxe6 Kf7 22. Rxf6+ Kxf6 23. Qh6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
