[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Bronstein, David I. vs. Dubinin, Peter Vasilievich, 1947"]
[Result "*"]

{ David Bronstein was a man of incredible imagination and the King's Gambit was one of his favorite openings. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. h4 g4 5. Ne5 h5 6. Bc4 Rh7 7. d4 Bh6
{ As we know from Chapter 8,  7...f3  8.gxf3  d6  is stronger. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9.
Nxf7 { White’s pieces are ready to join the attack very quickly. } 9... Rxf7
10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Bxf4 Bxf4 12. O-O { White's idea is based on this move. }
12... Qxh4 13. Rxf4+ Kg7 14. Qd2 d6 15. Raf1 Nd8 16. Nd5 Bd7 17. e5
{ All of White’s pieces are involved in the attack. } 17... dxe5 18. dxe5 Bc6
19. e6 { The black king is open to all winds now. } 19... Bxd5 20. Rf7+ Nxf7
21. Rxf7+ Kh8 22. Qc3+ Nf6 23. Rxf6 Qxf6 24. Qxf6+ Kh7 25. Qf5+ Kh6 26. Qxd5
Kg6 27. Qd7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Spassky, Boris V. vs. Bronstein, David I., 1960"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ It is believed that it was Bronstein who instilled in Spassky a love for the King's Gambit. In this game, the student defeated the teacher. }
1... e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 d5 4. exd5 Bd6 5. Nc3 Ne7 6. d4 O-O 7. Bd3 Nd7 8. O-O
h6
{ Up to this point, both sides have played quite logically. And here Spassky spices up the position by sacrificing a pawn. }
9. Ne4 Nxd5 10. c4 Ne3 11. Bxe3 fxe3 12. c5 Be7 13. Bc2
{ White is going to build a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal. } 13... Re8 14. Qd3
e2
{ 14...Nf8  Black desperately needed to cover the h7 square, but unfortunately Bronstein decided to buy himself some time... }
15. Nd6
{ Objectively this move does not win, but not everyone can decide to walk the black king to the center. }
15... Nf8
{ 15...exf1=Q+  16.Rxf1  Bxd6  17.Qh7+  Kf8  18.cxd6  cxd6  19.Qh8+  Ke7  20.Re1+  Ne5  21.Qxg7  Rg8  22.Qxh6  Qb6  23.Kh1  Be6  24.dxe5  Qf2!  25.exd6+  Kxd6  26.Qf4+  Ke7  and White is forced to be content with a perpetual check. }
16. Nxf7 { Now the attack is unstoppable. } 16... exf1=Q+ 17. Rxf1 Bf5
{ 17...Qd5  18.Bb3  Qh5  19.Nxh6+  Kh8  20.Nf7+  Kg8  21.N7g5+  Kh8  22.Bf7+- }
18. Qxf5 Qd7 19. Qf4 Bf6 20. N3e5 Qe7 21. Bb3 Bxe5 22. Nxe5+ Kh7 23. Qe4+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games & Afterword"]
[Black "Morozevich, Alexander vs. Anand, Viswanathan, PCA/Intel-GP Rapid, 1995"]
[Result "*"]

{ Alexander Morozevich is known as one of the most interesting and creative chess players of our time. Of course, he could not do without the King's Gambit in his repertoire. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bb3 d5 6. exd5 cxd5 7. d4 Bb4 8.
Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qc7 11. Qe1
{ White pulls his pieces towards the kingside. In this regard the h4-square looks perfect for the queen. }
11... Nc6 12. Qh4 Ne7 { Anand prepares to repel the siege. } 13. Bxf4 Qxc3 14.
Bd2 Qc7 15. Ne5 Nf5 16. Qf4 Be6 17. Bb4 Rfc8
{ Black repels the first wave of the attack, so Alexander begins to pull up those pieces that are not yet involved. }
18. g4 Nd6 19. Rae1
{ The position is very complex and double-edged, and here Vishy did not feel the main threat of White. }
19... Nfe4
{ 19...Nc4  20.g5  Nd7  21.Bxc4  Nxe5  22.Bxd5  Bxd5  23.Rxe5  Qc4  24.a3∞ }
20. c4 { Wonderful move! The light-squared bishop joins the attack too. } 20...
dxc4 21. Bc2 Nf6
{ 21...Qb6  22.Rxe4  Qxb4  23.Re3  and the white pieces look menacingly towards the black king. }
22. g5 Nh5
